fields.descriptive_line: Accessories from the Whiteladies dolls' house, made in England, 1935-1937
fields.physical_description: [Doll's house accessories] This small painting is of a grey and white interior, looking through an open door to an outside scene, down some railed steps to a grey landscape in the distance. The painting has an Art Deco chrome frame with fan shaped mouldings in the top two corners. The inscription on the back suggests this is the "grey bedroom". The architectural style of the bedroom interior is typically Art Deco, with white flat walls and curved features. The painting is rather crudely executed and does not appear  to have been undertaken by an experienced artist and could have been done by a child. This small painting is part of the accessories from the dolls' house known as  the Whiteladies dolls' house. The house itself and its furnishings were designed,  made or chosen to reflect the Art Deco contemporary style.
fields.dimensions: [Doll's house accessories] Height: 12.8 cm board, Width: 7.8 cm board, Height: 14.5 cm frame, Width: 9.1 cm frame
fields.title: Grey Bedroom
fields.history_note: Gift of Mrs Stanley Thomas, 1937. This painting is part of the Whiteladies dolls' house. The house was displayed at The Building Centre, 158, New Bond Street, W.1. between May 8th and May 29th, 1936 for charity. Funds raised went to the  Bond Street Ward of the Middlesex Hospital. A small publication entitled  'Whiteladies House (A Miniature Modern Home)' by Moray Thomas accompanied  the show. In 1937 it was offered to the Victoria ans Albert Museum as a gift having been on loan to the Children's Exhibition in the North Court in 1936. The house was intended to be a record in miniature of contemporary style.
